  "description": "A septum (plural: septa) is a cross-wall that divides a hypha into individual cells. In septate fungi — which include most Ascomycota and Basidiomycota — septa occur at regular intervals along the hypha, creating a chain of cells. Each septum typically has a central pore that allows cytoplasm, organelles, and even nuclei to flow between cells, maintaining the hypha as a functionally connected unit despite the physical partitions.\nNot all fungi have septa. Coenocytic fungi — including many Zygomycota and Chytridiomycota — grow as continuous tubes with no cross-walls, their hyphae containing many nuclei in a shared cytoplasm. The distinction between septate and coenocytic growth is one of the basic structural differences among fungal groups (see fungal taxonomy). Septate hyphae can seal their pores in response to damage, isolating injured cells and preventing cytoplasmic loss from spreading through the network. This gives septate fungi a damage-control mechanism that coenocytic fungi lack.\n",
  "keywords": "mycology, fungal-structure, cell-biology",
  "name": "Septum",
